Police raided the Nairobi home of a British national and arrested him alongside two Somali women. Police said during the operation, they found Al Shaabab literature. The arrested had rented a posh house at Rosslyn estate, where police said was the hideout of Al Shaabab recruiters and trainers. Sources said police found terror-related material from the house during the three-hour operation. A security guard said the Briton had lived in the house for three years, and was a regular traveller to Somalia. The operation was carried out by officers from the Flying Squad unit. READ MORE FOCUS TURNS TO GANATRA: As multiple top drivers keen to feature in National Rally Raid Murray dominates in Rio, outsider Puig arrives on big stage London lover who had child with Kenyan step-son quits